segments.text: Well, the tape has just stopped.
We'll turn it over.

And I was asking about the changes that occurred from the close of the Depression as it came to a close, giving way to World War II and these increasing demands and the incentive for all-out production, prices strengthening.
I wasn't conscious of when that happened.
But there wasn't a particular point in time when they said, well, look, we've got the depression whipped.
We've got a new problem here of increasing production.
No, we didn't have it that way.
We just eased into the...

For some of us who, I was a student in college during those periods, and now I look back on it, and we sometimes get the perspective that up to a certain time they're addressing this problem, and suddenly they got that solved, they got a whole new problem.
But you're saying that when you're out there on the farm and working with the farmers, the change wasn't all that great.
You know, farmers don't adjust so quickly.
Yes.
They learn how to do things, and they go right on doing them, even in times when things change.
Yes.
And it takes a mile for them to catch up with the change.
And I think that's true of all farmers.
Well, it's true of most of us.
I find myself having a hard time adjusting my teaching program to the computer.
I'm glad I don't have your problem.
But I see you've got your electronic hand calculator there that you operate.
I don't have the controls there.
Oh, that controls.
I thought maybe you balanced your checkbook with that.
Oh, no.
I see.
I don't have enough money to worry about.
Well, actually, I don't either.
I find that the less money I have, the more I have to worry about it and the more carefully I have to plan.
Let me ask you a question or two, though, about the kind of adjustments that have taken place.
You were involved with research when irrigation came into the high plains, weren't you?
No.
How did that all take place?
Was it very rapidly?
I wish I could get an answer to that first.
Relatively so.
It came quite rapidly along toward the close of the 1930s and 40s?
Late 30s, 1940s.
That had a tremendous impact on that part of the state, didn't it?
Increased their worries.
increased their worries, their costs.
They lost a lot of the flexibility they used to have.
Land prices rose substantially.
One set of troubles to another.
Their type of farming changed too, didn't it, some?
Well, they're still growing cotton.
That was dry land cotton before, and they chained over it.
Were they growing corn before?
No.
So corn came in with that, didn't it?
And then their sorghum production increased very rapidly, very substantially.
And then that gave rise to the cattle feeding.
See, it didn't take much water, sorghum and corn.
The cattle feeding then soon followed after irrigation, didn't it?
Yeah, I wasn't conscious of the cattle feeding until the 1940s.
Then there was the biggest, probably the biggest area of transition was in East Texas, wasn't it?
What was farming like in East Texas when you came down here?
Well, it was all in little farms.
10, 15 acres of cotton.
I see.
And these were not only on the riverbeds, but everywhere?
What about on this land around College Station and between here and Huntsville?
Would much of that land be farmed in small farms, or was that cultivated?
When you talk about East Texas, I don't include that.
You go further east, yes.
Trinity.
On the Trinity River, up in that way.
Well, in what I call East Texas, farming went out completely.
Yes.
A little 10, 15 acres of cotton.
about the same amount of corn, and a lot of little farmers, too.
Well, the whole thing went out.
Yes.
Were these primarily these small operations, were they tenant farmers for the most part?
Sharecroppers?
Well, it wasn't up there to share.
I see.
I see.
I see.
Did, in that, you made a study
of East Texas, didn't you?
Along in the very early late 20s or early 30s?
Early 30s.
In the early 30s.
That's the first area that we studied when I came to Texas.
I see.
What was your conclusion?
Do you recall what your conclusions were about cotton farming then, its future?
That was an important cotton producing area of the state then, was it?
Yes.
First one and then another one.
give up farming.
And that land would be, I always thought of Houston people buying the land and taking it out of farming.
It's a fairly gradual process.
It's either farms
They were different ages, and those farmers had to go out of business or die off.
Yeah.
And put a piece of land on the operator, farming it.
Nobody else wanted it.
Nobody would take it on to grow cotton.
To grow cotton, yeah.
So the gins had a real rough time then.
Oh, yeah.
I don't suppose there's any gins in East Texas.
Probably not.
But during that time of transition, the cotton industry, as I recall, that is my recollection of the cotton industry, is that it was a very strong, outspoken industry.
They were highly organized at the industry level.
The gins, the ginners, the marketers, did they
How did they react to your studies that says cotton can't survive in this area?
I don't remember any trouble with those people.
You didn't have any problems with them?
No.
I guess I was fortunate in that I had Bill Morgan.
Yes.
And he was in good with the extension service, and particularly with Williams.
And I think Bill, for a while, was in and he said in the extension service.
But as I
Somehow I've had the impression that when your studies first predicted that along about the end of the 30s that cotton was going to be going out, that there were some people from the
in the cotton industry that might have given you guys a pretty bad time and wanted your research stopped.
If it was, I wasn't aware of it.
I see.
And this Bill Morgan.
Yes.
He stood in especially well with the director of the extension service.
And when he said anything, that was it.
Mm-hmm.
He and I worked very closely.
Yes.

So if you really didn't experience, so far as you were concerned, as a researcher, you didn't have any spokesman, any opposition out there coming to the administration and say, look, we think you ought to get Bonnen off of this cotton research in East Texas.
No.
Uh-huh.
See, but at the same time, Bill Morgan was in the Extension Service.
Uh-huh.
Well, that's interesting.

Sometimes, you know, when what you're saying, when your research points out some changes that are coming about, those people who have something to lose from those changes get pretty vocal and try to bring pressure to bear.
You didn't experience that kind of influence.
Big losers were the Jenners and people like that.
Yes, the cotton merchants.
And they were sort of swept out of it.
Yes.
But they didn't influence, they didn't try to slow down that process by having your...
I wasn't conscious of it, I'll say it.
By having your stuff stopped.
This area of adjustment has been a constant one for Texas, hasn't it?
Oh, yeah.
Probably more so than most other areas.
Yeah.
East Texas, south Texas.
Yes.
Then adjusting to water up in the panhandle.
Yeah.
And then adjusting...
As water's getting used up, they've got to adjust back now.
There's another big adjustment that's coming.
I don't know whether they can make that adjustment or not.
Yes.
Did you know Frank Hughes?
Did you work with Frank Hughes quite a bit?
Frank was with USDA when I came here.

I had always had the feeling that if I could just tap Frank's mind and the recesses of his understanding, I could probably learn more about the water supplies and how it was used in the Panhandle, Texas, than just about any other source of information.
You could get a good deal.
Yes.
Unfortunately, I never did get it.
I went to him just at the time when he was retiring and with a series of questions and said, is there any way that we could get you to write a manuscript
covering your research up here.
And somehow Frank had been offended either by university administration or by USDA.
And he says, I've got only one thing in my mind, and that is to quit and never get involved again.
They've got their last word out of me.
So we didn't quite get him to get down all that he had learned.
Right.
Yeah.
Well, Mr. Bonin.
I think people in research tend to get it a little better than they do in the extension of life.
I guess the extension serves to deal with more individuals.
I've never been conscious of the much difference, the difference of opinion among the surgery people.
Research people don't deal with as many individuals as the extension people do.
Yes.
And in research, you're not always needing to sell yourself as you sell your message.
No.
As they are in extension.
And maybe that's one reason.
Here it is.
You can either take it or leave it.
I feel that way.
Yes.
Yes, I think so.
You've had a very fruitful career, Mr. Bonin.
Very productive.
You were part of a small research group that was probably unique in history.
I have reviewed that period when there was you
Of course, under Mr. Gabbard, Paulson, just the three of you there for a while, and they comprised most of that research group.
Yet, your productivity in terms of publications is phenomenal.
Not only were they the typical bulletins, but you had
a large number of publications in referee journals.
I believe on that the number of referee journals that were put out by your group was per say over a decade
was almost as large as it was during the decade, say, of the 50s, when the staff was much, much larger, say, five or six times larger.
Perhaps it was because you were focused so sharply on the research problems and not diverted
Maybe, I don't know.
Perhaps it was just the unique individuals that were there.
Mr. Gabbard apparently was a good researcher.
Paulson surely was.
Very productive, wasn't he?
Paulson was an individual that you had to know to appreciate.
I don't know whether you've ever
seen them enough in the old experiments, the main experiment station building.
We had room size safes that you could lock and they had metal shelves all around the sides and he and I shared one of those.
I see.
And before things had gotten
Not along too far.
He had all these shelves covered with reports and so on.
And I had one little shelf there.
He just kept moving around with one shelf and another.
It was safe.
He pulled a lot of material.
He ran in trouble.
But he collected all kinds of stuff that he never used.
Yes.
He'd just keep putting it on the shelves and leaving it there.
I wonder if that isn't true of marketing people generally.
Maybe, I don't know.
I've never made a study of that.
I haven't either, but I've, of the most
eclectic people in our profession that I've got to know who gather great volumes.
Many of them are marketing, involved in marketing, and maybe that's...
There's just a lot of relevant data and arguments that they think they're going to have to have reference to.
Well, Mr. Bonin, I've taken...

an hour and a half of your time here and it's been very rewarding you look back on on your profession do you have any any recollections or any feelings about how this profession has changed this is going to be the 75th we are going to be entering the 75th year since the since the
Association began professionally.
It's expanded a great deal, but how else?
Do you see some ways, do you recall ways, or have some sense of ways in which it has changed?
Not having thought much about those things.
There's a heck of a lot more people working there.
Yes.
It has become far more diverse.
There are lots of sub-disciplines now, whereas when you began, there was marketing and farm management, and then general policy, finance.
Your son, Jim, has distinguished himself notably in the profession, primarily in the area of policy, and quite clearly, policy has been important from the beginning.
But there are now many other sub-disciplines.
It's become more quantitative, I guess.
Yeah, I think so.
You began.
It's become far more quantitative since I began.
I finished my Ph.D. in 1954, and I'm glad I don't have to pass the exams that these students today have to take.
So it's changing.
Certainly is.
If you come across any items, pictures, or memorabilia that you think would be of interest to our profession, why, let us know about them.
I think I have a picture of the department, taken of the department.
